rticular matter or physical form in which it is materially represented or mentally visualized? How do sacral or divine "things" act, and what is the source and nature of their agency? How might we productively define and think about anthropomorphism in relation to the divine? What is the relationship between the mental and the material image, and between the categories of object and image, image and likeness, and likeness and representation? Drawing on a broad range of written and pictorial sources, this volume is a novel contribution to the contemporary discourse on the functioning and communicative potential of the material and materialized divine as it is developing in the fields of anthropology, art history, and the history and cognitive science of religion.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aMaterialismxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and culture. 4aAgency. 4aAnthropomorphism. 4aMateriality. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh1 aPongratz-Leisten, Beate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSonik, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97815015023090 cprintz978150151068740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150226240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501502262423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501502262.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEB